methylation inhibitors","Histone deacetylase enzymes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe generation of induced pluripotent stem cells requires the \u003Cstrong\u003Etranscription factors OCT4, SOX2, KLF4, and c-MYC\u003C/strong\u003E. These factors reprogram the cell\u0027s gene expression pattern to restore pluripotency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmbryonic stem cell extract\u003C/strong\u003E - Cell extracts alone cannot reliably induce pluripotency\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth factors and hormones\u003C/strong\u003E - Growth factors alone cannot induce pluripotency without genetic reprogramming\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDNA methylation inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E - While these may enhance reprogramming, they are not sufficient alone\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHistone deacetylase enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - These enzymes regulate gene expression but cannot induce pluripotency\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe discovery of induced pluripotent stem cells has revolutionised stem cell research by providing an ethical alternative to embryonic stem cells and enabling patient-specific cell therapy development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pluripotent stem cells can differentiate into any cell type except placental tissue.","Induced pluripotent stem cells are created by reprogramming adult cells using specific transcription factors.","The key transcription factors for inducing pluripotency are OCT4, SOX2, KLF4, and c-MYC."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Schmidt R, Plath K. The roles of the reprogramming factors Oct4, Sox2 and Klf4 in resetting the somatic cell epigenome during induced pluripotent stem cell generation. Genome Biol. 2012 Oct 22;13(10):251. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3491406/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17248"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:03:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T11:05:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9938"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69576"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udee7","name":"Cell Biology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,